Title:
An Idealistic View of Malware Analysis Definitions (WTF is heuristics?)

Type:
Blog Post

Short Summary (4–8 sentences max):
- This post clarifies commonly-misunderstood malware analysis and detection terms: static analysis, dynamic analysis, heuristics, and “deterministic” (signature-like) detections.  
- It frames static analysis as non-executing inspection of file bytes/structure (e.g., PE parsing) and dynamic analysis as execution-based observation (sandbox/emulator/EDR) of in-memory artifacts and runtime actions.  
- Heuristics are described as “looks malicious” scoring/triage signals (entropy anomalies, suspicious imports/traits, generic patterns) rather than definitive proof, while deterministic detections are precise indicators with low false positives (e.g., unique YARA strings, known-bad hashes).  
- The article highlights that “signature” rules can be either heuristic or deterministic depending on how specific the matched indicator is and how it’s interpreted.  
- It also discusses behavioral detection via hooks/ETW (e.g., LSASS handle opens vs. actual credential-reading) and the ambiguous classification of emulation (“static emulation” vs dynamic).  
- Useful for both red and blue teams to reason about why detections fire, where false positives come from, and how context changes interpretation.

Technical Focus:
- Static file analysis (PE parsing, imports/sections/headers)
- Dynamic analysis (sandboxing, memory scanning, behavior observation)
- Heuristic vs deterministic/signature-based detection models (scoring/thresholds)
- YARA rule specificity and false-positive tradeoffs
- Behavioral telemetry via API hooking and ETW
- Emulation as a hybrid analysis technique

Use Cases:
- Calibrating YARA/signature rules to reduce false positives while retaining coverage
- Explaining AV/EDR alert rationale to analysts and stakeholders
- Red team planning around heuristic triggers (e.g., LSASS access, injection-like behavior)
- Designing detection logic that separates “suspicious” from “high-confidence malicious”
- Choosing appropriate analysis methods (static vs sandbox vs endpoint telemetry) during triage

Keywords:
static analysis, dynamic analysis, heuristics, deterministic detection, signature-based detection, YARA, PE (Portable Executable), imports, entropy, sandbox, emulator, memory scanning, behavior analysis, EDR, ETW, ntdll hooking, LSASS, OpenProcess, code injection, mimikatz, SHA256, MD5